DRAFT

1 Background

Returning natural-origin and hatchery-origin Chinook Salmon to the Lostine River are intercepted by a permanent trapping facility. After each fish is captured, facility staff decide to release the fish either upstream to spawn naturally, or to keep them for future use as brood stock or as an outplant to downstream tributaries to the Wallowa River. The decision to release the fish upstream or to keep them is guided by a weir management sliding scale that seeks to balance the contributions of natural-origin fish to hatchery production, and hatchery-origin fish to natural production at various escapement levels. We initiated this work to more thoroughly understand the impacts of the weir management sliding scale on total returns and allotted harvest. Because the weir sliding scale limits the number or proportion of hatchery origin spawners (pHOS) we hypothesized removing the constraint of pHOS would increase natural production and total returns to the Lostine River, and ultimately a greater number of fish available for harvest.

We developed a life-cycle simulation model to examine differences in escapement and harvest under five management scenarios. The first scenario follows our current baseline conditions with an integrated hatchery program of 175 brood stock with spawner composition determined by the weir management sliding scale, and harvest being implemented at the maximum allowed level determined by harvest sliding scales. The second scenario used the weir sliding scale to determine the same number of natural-origin broodstock as scenario 1, but differed by allowing an unconstrained pHOS (i.e., all remaining hatchery origin fish were allowed to spawn naturally). The third scenario used the same weir sliding scale as scenario 1 to determine brood stock and naturally spawning composition but didnâ€™t allow harvest (i.e., set harvest to zero). The forth and fifth scenarios eliminated the hatchery program and assumed all fish spawned naturally and only differed by either allowing harvest or excluding harvest.

2 Results and Conclusions

2.1 Weir Management Sliding Scale

  1. Under the current baseline conditions the model stabilizes at:
  2. 1,500 hatchery-origin fish and 500 natural-origin fish returning,
  3. harvest or natural-origin adults is 19, and 150 hatchery-origin adults are harvested.
  4. Hatchery-origin escapement is unchanged when the weir management sliding scale is removed, or when harvest is not allowed.
  5. Natural-origin escapement is approximately 250 individuals without the hatchery program (i.e., half the return with the hatchery program).
  6. Zero harvest occurs without the hatchery program.

3 Methods

3.1 Life-cycle Model

The developed model incorporates 5 life stages and stochasticity using a Monte-Carlo simulation approach. The simulation randomly samples variables from known probability distributions to gain inference about an unknown outcome (Gentle 2015). After the random variables are drawn we use them in deterministic functions to make probabilistic inferences at the life stages of interest (Manly and Manly 2017). Model design follows a stream type Chinook salmon life cycle in Idaho (grootPacificSalmonLife1991?) and simulates variable abundance by sampling productivity metrics from previously fitted models of natural and hatchery origin stock-recruit relationships, smolt-to-adult return rate, and age compositions using observed data from the Lostine River.

Model inputs cover five key areas: (1) supplementation program design and weir management, (2) spawner success and juvenile productivity, (3) smolt-to-adult return rates, (4) age composition of adult returns, and (5) tributary harvest exploitation rates. Model outputs include total tributary abundance by origin and age, brood stock collection and spawner composition, and harvest opportunities available for the simulated return.

The model simulates natural and hatchery abundance across time by estimating progeny returns with either fixed or random prespawn mortality, juvenile productivity, SARs, and age at return values. Setting these four parameters as fixed, informs the model to return expected values of abundance across time; removing stochasticity. In contrast, Monte Carlo simulations can be used to introduce stochasticity in abundance by randomly sampling parameters from known probability distributions.

The model begins by determining the maximum proportion of adult hatchery-origin spawners (\(pHOS\)) allowed upstream of the weir, and the proportion of natural-origin fish allowed within the hatchery brood stock (\(pNOB\)). The proportions are determined by the estimated number of natural-origin adults returning to the tributary (\(N^{Trib}_{NOR}\)) and the agreed upon weir management sliding scale (??)(NEED CITATION).

Natural and hatchery origin adults kept for broodstock or released upstream to spawn naturally are determined by a weir management sliding scale and the number of fish returning to the Lostine River.

Within the model, we assummed the number of natural-origin (\(NOR\)) and hatchery-origin (\(HOR\)) adult fish harvested, is determined by \(N^{Trib}_{NOR}\) and the agreed upon sport and tribal tributary harvest exploitation rates (NEED CITATION). Table ?? shows the exploitation rates used in the model for fish in excess of the closest lower rate. For example, if the natural-origin return was 500 adults, then harvest would equal \((300 * .01) + (500 - 300) * .08 = 19\).

Abundance Harvest Rate on Hatchery Excess Harvest on Natural Excess

For each origin {\(O\)}, the number of actual adult fish surviving to the weir, \(N^{Weir}\), and available for brood stock collection and release upstream becomes,

\[ N^{Weir}_O = N^{Trib}_O - h^{}_O. \] The number of natural-origin brood stock (\(BS_{NOR}\)) is then calculated using the designated \(pNOB\) from the weir management sliding scale (??),

\[ BS_{NOR} = N^{Weir}_{NOR} * pNOB. \] and, hatchery-origin brood stock (\(BS_{HOR}\)) becomes the remainder of the total brood stock need (\(BS\)),

\[ BS_{HOR} = BS - BS_{NOR}. \]

The total number of fish successfully contributing to hatchery production (\(S^{Hatchery}\)) is then a random variable from a binomial distribution with an assumed prespawn mortality rate in the hatchery environment (\(p^{Hatchery}\)) and \(BS\).

\[ S^{Hatchery} \sim Binom(p^{Hatchery}, BS) \]

Natural-origin adult fish released upstream of the weir to spawn naturally is

\[ N^{Released}_{NOR} = N^{Weir}_{NOR} - BS_{NOR}, \] while, hatchery-origin fish released upstream to spawn naturally is controlled by the weir management sliding scale and the set maximum proportion of hatchery-origin spawners (\(pHOS_{max}\)),

\[ N^{Released}_{HOR} = \frac{(-pHOS_{max} * S_{NOR})}{pHOS_{max} - 1}. \] Excess hatchery-origin adults removed (\(R_{HOR}\)) from the system and not available for future production then becomes,

\[ R_{HOR} = N^{Weir}_{HOR} - BS_{HOR} - N^{Released}_{HOR}. \] The number of fish contributing to natural production (\(S\)) is a random variable from a binomial distribution with an assumed prespawn mortality rate in nature (\(p^{Nature}\)) and the total spawners released.

\[ S^{Nature} \sim Binom(p^{Nature}, N^{Released}_{NOR} + N^{Released}_{HOR}) \] Juvenile productivity in nature follows a Beverton-Holt density dependent function, where \(S^{Nature}\) represents the stock and natural-origin juvenile recruits (\(J_{NOR}\)) are smolt surviving to Lower Granite Dam.

\[ J_{NOR} = \frac{\alpha S}{1 + \beta S} \] The parameter \(\alpha\) represents the maximum recruitment rate at low spawning abundances and \(\beta\) is the density-dependent parameter that governs the functions shape.

The ratio of hatchery-origin smolt surviving to Lower Granite Dam from \(S^{Hatchery}\) is sampled from a log-normal distribution as follows,

\[ \phi \sim LogNormal(\mu_\phi, \sigma_\phi) \]

where, \(\mu_\phi\) and \(\sigma_\phi\) is estimated from observed data. Hatchery-origin juvenile smolts surviving to Lower Granite Dam then becomes \(R_{HOR} = S^{Hatchery} * \phi\).

The Monte-Carlo model was written in the statistical computing language R (R Core Team 2014) and available in an R package at https://github.com/NPTfisheries/Chinook-Life-Cycle.

3.2.3 Smolt-to-Adult Return Rates

We modeled smolt-to-adult return (SAR) rates and their covariance between natural and hatchery origin fish with a linear mixed effects model (Zuur et al. 2009). Similar to Bosch et al. (2023), a logit link was used to estimate the SAR proportions as a linear function of the fixed effect origin and the random effect of brood_year.

3.4 indicates natural origin SARs are typically higher than hatchery origin and range from 0.0064779, 0.0757901. Hatchery origin SARs range from 0.0028418, 0.0436594 and on average are only 41% of the natural origin SAR.

Figure 3.4: Brood year estimates of smolt to adult return (SAR) rates for Lostine River natural and hatchery origin returns. The mean SAR for each origin is shown in black with the associated 95% confidence intervals.

SAR predictions generated from the fitted SAR model are shown in 3.5. Predictions are derived using the uncertainty and covariance in fixed effects parameters and the random brood year effects.

Figure 3.5: Smolt-to-adult return predictions based on the best fitting model and random brood year effects.

3.2.4 Age at Return

Age-at-return was modeled with three age categories (i.e., 3, 4, and 5) using multinomial logistic models (Agresti 2003) with terms for origin, brood year, and the origin by brood year interaction. We determined the full model was the best fit when compared against model subsets with an analysis of deviance. The model indicated natural origin age 3 returns were relatively decreasing while older age 4 and 5 fish are increasing (3.6. Hatchery origin fish showed steep decreases in age 3 and age 5 returns with a steep increase in age 4 returns.
